<HEADLINE>
FT  15 DEC 93 / Forte closes in on Ciga as competition falls off
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SKAPINKER, Leisure Industries Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Forte's chances of acquiring the Italian-based Ciga luxury hotel chain rose
last night when Host Marriott of the US withdrew its competing bid.
Host Marriott said it had suspended negotiations to acquire Ciga because it
had been given insufficient information to counter Forte's offer.
ITT Sheraton, which had also expressed some interest in Ciga, said last
night that it had not submitted a bid for the chain.
Forte executives are expected to make a presentation today to Mediobanca,
the Milan merchant bank that has organised a restructuring of the highly
indebted Ciga.
Forte said last October that it had agreed to take over the management of
Ciga, which has net debts of more than L1,000bn (Pounds 397m).
Under the agreement Forte said it would pay Pounds 33m cash and insert some
of its own luxury hotels with a value of about Pounds 125m into an Italian
operating company, in which it would have a majority interest.
Ciga's bank debt would be transferred into a separate property holding
company in which the operating company would have a 15 per cent stake.
The deal would give Forte access to a prestigious luxury hotel brand -
something it sought in the 1980s with its bid for the Savoy group. The
agreement to manage Ciga raised questions over whether Forte would need to
continue its pursuit of Savoy. Ciga has 35 hotels in Italy, Austria, France,
Greece, the Netherlands and Spain.
Some of Ciga's creditor banks were unhappy with the Forte agreement,
however, and criticised Mediobanca for not examining alternatives. Barclays
of the UK was believed to have been one of the most vociferous critics of
the agreement with Forte.
Host Marriott emerged as the most credible rival to Forte last month when it
said it was in discussions over the possible acquisition of Ciga. It said
Marriott International, its sister company, could run some or all of the
hotels.
Although ITT Sheraton said a bid for Ciga was under 'preliminary review',
Host Marriott's discussions with Ciga were seen as a more potent threat to
Forte.
Forte, which has been conducting its due diligence investigations of Ciga,
argued that it had more experience of running luxury hotels than the other
two groups.
</TEXT>
