<HEADLINE>
FT  15 DEC 93 / Trafalgar House loses Pounds 347m: Rights issue to raise
Pounds 404m - Charges total Pounds 468m / 1p payout this year
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Simon Keswick, chairman of Trafalgar House, yesterday described the
group's Pounds 425m rights issue and placing as a 'fresh start' for the
troubled conglomerate that posted a pre-tax loss of Pounds 347.2m in the
year to September 30.
The loss, which compares with a restated pre-tax deficit of Pounds 11.2m,
was struck after the group recorded exceptional charges totalling Pounds
397.3m (Pounds 97.3m), comprising asset write-downs, property provisions and
rationalisation costs. Shares in Trafalgar, which has interests ranging from
engineering and construction to London's Ritz Hotel and the Cunard liners,
fell by 10p to close at 77 1/2 p yesterday.
Mr Keswick, who is also chairman of Hongkong Land Holdings, which holds a
25.3 per cent stake in Trafalgar, said the Pounds 404m net proceeds of the
1-for-3 convertible preference share issue and placing would provide the
group with 'a strong and transparent balance sheet'. The Pounds 70m placing
was designed to attract new institutional investors to the group. 'It is all
part of starting afresh,' he said.
Hongkong Land, which has already invested about Pounds 200m in its Trafalgar
equity stake, said it planned to take up its full entitlement at a cost of
about Pounds 90m. It would also apply for additional shares under the
placing.
The announcements underline the degree to which Hongkong Land dominates
Trafalgar's new management team, which took over from Sir Nigel Broackes,
the former chairman, and Sir Eric Parker, former chief executive, last year.
In addition to Mr Keswick, Hongkong Land's four board representatives
include Mr David Gawler as finance director. Mr Keswick insisted that the
extensive write-downs and provisions did not represent a 'kitchen sink'
approach to the accounts.
He described them as 'just normal prudent accounting'.
The new board's review of the balance sheet led to write-downs and
provisions of Pounds 330.7m, including provisions announced at the interim
stage of Pounds 100m. Asset write-downs charged to revaluation reserves
added Pounds 39.8m.
A change in accounting policy on capitalising finance charges added Pounds
30.6m to exceptional items, rationalisation programmes Pounds 65.3m and
directors' compensation payments Pounds 1.3m. The charges totalled Pounds
467.7m.
Although substantial property and other provisions had been expected, some
elements were a surprise - for instance, Pounds 42.1m for its ill-fated
Emerald oil rig, Pounds 22.3m for group properties and Pounds 17.5m to cover
early repayment of costly debt.
Over all these charges swamped the group's Pounds 77.5m of operating
profits, down from Pounds 126.8m. Turnover was flat at Pounds 3.88bn.
The 47.6p loss per share compares with a 12.2p loss. A final dividend of 2p
makes a total of 3.25p, against 6p. However, shareholders were told to
expect a total of not more than 1p for the current year.
Lex, Page 18; Rebuilding Trafalgar, Page 20; Hot potato, Page 20
</TEXT>
