<HEADLINE>
FT  15 DEC 93 / Noble Lowndes fined Pounds 740,000 over poor investment
advice
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Noble Lowndes and Partners, the financial adviser, has been fined Pounds
740,000 by City regulators for breaches of rules, including giving bad
advice to customers.
Imro, the self-regulatory organisation for the investment management
industry, said yesterday that the firm had admitted four disciplinary
charges.
As well as the fine, Noble Lowndes must pay Imro's costs of Pounds 45,000
for the disciplinary action. So far it has also paid out Pounds 580,000 in
compensation to customers.
NLP said that the charges of giving unsuitable advice and 'churning' -
buying and selling shares under management for no other reason than to earn
commission - related to the activities of four personal financial services
consultants. None of the four, who operated from offices in Leeds and the
Midlands, is still working for NLP.
Between May 1988 and February 1992 they engaged in 'systematic' switching of
investments between products in ways that 'were not justified from the
customer's objective'. Altogether, 225 clients were involved.
Imro launched a formal investigation in April this year to examine possible
breaches of its rules from one branch office which had been drawn to its
attention by NLP's internal audit.
In consultation with Imro, NLP appointed the accountancy firm Binder Hamlyn
to conduct a thorough review of all the client files concerned. When it is
finished in about six months, its investigation will have covered samples
from the files of up to a third of the 240 sales consultants employed over
the relevant period.
Imro also found that NLP had failed to keep proper written records on, for
example, customers' circumstances or their understanding of the investment
risk, and it criticised the procedures for monitoring compliance and for
identifying potential 'churning' of customers.
All the costs are to be met by the TSB group, which sold Noble Lowndes to
Sedgwick, its present owner, in September for Pounds 110m.
Mr Robert Walker, managing director of personal financial services at NLP,
said yesterday that the charges related to single-premium investment
products, such as bonds or unit trusts.
Although NLP provides actuarial consultancy services for the pensions
industry as well as giving financial advice, the mis-selling did not relate
to pensions business.
Mr Walker and Mr David Strauss, NLP's chief executive, highlighted the
changes in compliance procedures and in management that Sedgwick had made,
and emphasised its commitment to ensuring that all clients were fully
compensated.
In June, Imro imposed a Pounds 750,000 fine on Invesco MIM, the fund
management group, which admitted 55 breaches of City rules.
</TEXT>
