<HEADLINE>
FT  15 DEC 93 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Does it matter that many of the programmes made under BBC2's Bookmark
umbrella have been so good that the series has now won the right to make
programmes in which the 'book' content may be a bit hard to find? No it
doesn't. Excellence is always to be welcomed, and anyway there is invariably
some bookish connection. For today's programme they took Israeli writer
David Grossman into the Occupied Territories on the day after Israel
recognised the PLO to discuss the moral aspects of the Arab/Israeli conflict
(8.00).
Crime Story has not been the greatest series of its sort, but today's 'real
life' episode is a memorable one. When clothes belonging to Labour
politician John Stonehouse were found on a Miami beach some assumed he had
committed suicide, but others said 'Who's he trying to kid?' Sure enough, he
had sloped off to Australia and was later brought back to face trial (9.00
ITV).
In Stark Ben Elton, writer adaptor and star of this story about businessmen
scheming to take over the world, is still trying to get the celibate Rachel
into bed (9.25 BBC2).
</TEXT>
