<HEADLINE>
FT  15 DEC 93 / Terror reinsurer collects Pounds 100m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Pool Re, the specialist terrorist damage reinsurer set up after commercial
insurers withdrew from the market, has collected more than Pounds 100m in
premiums, it emerged yesterday.
More than 159 insurers have been admitted to the scheme and a further 75
applications could be accepted by the end of the year, the company said.
The apparent success of the new arrangement comes after earlier threats by
insurers that they would refuse to support it.
It also suggests that the government's contribution as a backstop on claims
for terrorist damage that Pool Re cannot support will be minimal.
Insurers expressed concerns in the summer about the structure of Pool Re,
and over a lack of consultation with the sector by the DTI.
Mr Keith Loney, company secretary, said that Pool Re now had Pounds 100m
invested. Substantial additional amounts would be provided by insurers by
early in the new year.
He said Pool Re had so far paid out only Pounds 29m on claims relating to
the Bishopsgate bomb in April. He estimated the total could be Pounds 300m.
Pool Re also expects claims from the Bournemouth bombing in August of about
Pounds 2m.
The first set of accounts for the company will not be published until
spring, but Mr Loney said its annual administrative costs were less than
Pounds 1m. Pool Re last increased its premiums - which are passed on at the
same rate by the insurers to policyholders - in July. Mr Loney said
Commercial insurers would absorb the first Pounds 100,000 in claims before
Pool Re paid out.
The NatWest Tower in the City of London, damaged by an IRA bomb in April
this year, is to be refurbished next year.
</TEXT>
