<HEADLINE>
FT  15 DEC 93 / Day of frantic telephone diplomacy brings accord
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
It was a day of frantic telephone diplomacy.
By the time Downing Street aides summoned lobby journalists to a remote nook
of the Palace of Westminster at 8.11pm to signal that a declaration had been
agreed - bar a few uncrossed t's and undotted i's  - prime minister Mr John
Major and his Irish counterpart had spoken twice. Some of their officials
had been on the line far more frequently.
The result was confirmation that the Major-Reynolds roadshow, which had
taken in Brussels, Dublin and Brussels again in little more than six weeks
would reconvene - they hoped in triumph - in London today.
The language the aides used was still cautious. 'Some details', they said,
had still to be 'sorted out'. But it was clear that - barring an
extraordinary setback - the two premiers will today unveil the long-promised
joint declaration that they hope will pave the way for peace.
The cautious aides 'expect' the prime minister to brief MPs on developments
in the afternoon.
The prime minister's day of detailed, last-minute haggling on Ulster started
about 10am when he met Mr Douglas Hurd, foreign secretary, Mr Michael
Ancram, Northern Ireland minister, Sir Robin Butler, the cabinet secretary,
and others. Sir Patrick Mayhew, the Northern Ireland secretary, was in
Belfast.
At 10.25am the first 15-minute phone call between Mr Major and Mr Reynolds
took place. Some square brackets cordoning off sensitive areas of text in
the unfinished declaration were rubbed out.
But more remained to be done. It was decided that the two leaders would have
to speak again later in the day.
In the meantime Mr Major had to deal with prime minister's questions in the
House of Commons where, curiously, the situation in the province did not
crop up - although the Rev Martyn Smyth, the Ulster Unionist MP for South
Belfast, made a dogged and unsuccessful attempt to catch the Speaker's eye.
The second conversation came about 4pm. Some progress was made in the course
of a 'constructive' 10-minute exchange. But not enough. Aides were saying at
4.30pm that a third conversation between the leaders might be necessary.
This turned out to be pessimistic. Officials were able to clear enough of
the remaining logjam for the lobby journalists to be summoned.
Mr Reynolds will arrive at Downing Street at 11am today and - perhaps - make
history.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
    IEZ  Ireland, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P9721 International Affairs.
</IN>
