<HEADLINE>
FT  15 DEC 93 / Sensing centre to be probed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DANIEL GREEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The National Remote Sensing Centre, a part of Britain's space establishment
which was privatised last year, is to be investigated following a report by
the National Audit Office, the government's spending watchdog, Daniel Green
writes.
The report, published yesterday, says that the centre, majority controlled
by British Aerospace, could have a 'privileged position' because it may be
able to take competitive advantage of the close links it still has with the
British National Space Centre, a government agency.
The BNSC is expected to start its costing and pricing investigation into the
sensing centre soon.
The sensing centre, which made a pre-tax profit of Pounds 389,000 on sales
of Pounds 4.1m last year, said it was aware that other space-sector
companies were wary of its position but any fears were unfounded. It said it
would, however, re-examine its costing and charging schemes.
The NAO report broadly praised the UK's space policy.
Department of Trade and Industry: Support of Earth Observation Technology.
National Audit Office. HMSO. Pounds 7.40.
