<HEADLINE>
FT  15 DEC 93 / Rolls-Royce 'viable' with sales of 1,500 cars a year
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GRIFFITHS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sales of Rolls-Royce and Bentley cars are unlikely to exceed 1,500 a year -
compared with a peak of 3,333 in 1990 - 'for the foreseeable future',
according to Mr Michael Donovan, commercial managing director of the
Vickers-owned luxury car maker.
But with the company's break-even output, including substantial provision
for research and development, down to 1,300, it is viable, Mr Donovan said.
The prediction made in the summer by Sir Colin Chandler, Vickers' chief
executive, that Rolls-Royce would return to profitability this year - after
running up total pre-tax losses of Pounds 110m in 1991 and 1992 - is being
borne out by the level of year-end sales, Mr Donovan said.
The company last made a profit, of Pounds 32m, in 1990.
He disclosed that Rolls-Royce's financial performance was being boosted
strongly by the unexpected success of the Pounds 170,000 Bentley Continental
coupe model, which is said to account for 20 per cent of output.
The company's 'standard' model, the Rolls-Royce Silver Spirit, sells for
about Pounds 100,000.
Sir Colin has said that in the long term Rolls-Royce Motor Cars would need
to find some form of partnership to develop a new generation of models. Mr
Donovan said it was possible that future model developments would be
achieved through a number of partnership projects.
He indicated that, in the longer term, the company could make wider use of
aluminium, new lightweight steels and possibly even diesel engines to
accommodate energy and environmental concerns.
Given the pace of diesel engine development, 'one should never say never
when it comes to one being fitted to Rolls-Royce'.
</TEXT>
