<HEADLINE>
FT  15 DEC 93 / Accounting standards changes planned
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Accounting standards-setters will produce proposals for changes to the
reporting of pension-fund costs and deferred taxation during the next few
months, the Financial Reporting Council's annual review said yesterday,
Andrew Jack writes.
The Accounting Standards Board, a subsidiary of the council, will also
examine related-party transactions and the treatment of associates and joint
ventures as part of an ambitious programme.
The review shows that the Financial Reporting Review Panel, the accounting
watchdog controlled by the council, considered 45 cases in the past year, as
well as 19 cases outstanding at the start of the year. Eleven were not
pursued, and there was action on 42 of the remaining cases.
Sir Ron Dearing, chairman of the council, says in the review that financial
reporting is being taken seriously by all company board members.
A number of 'corporate disasters' had shown the need for financial reporting
to serve shareholders, creditors and employees better, he says.
The review rejects any suggestion that the Accounting Standards Board is
focusing on balance sheets at the expense of profit and loss accounts, or
moving towards a system of current-cost accounting.
It says the board will revise its process for ratifying statements of
recommended practice developed by outside bodies, with new sub-committees to
consider proposals in financial services and for non- profit-making
organisations.
It adds that the board will ask early next year for comments on the
operation of its first financial reporting standard on the cashflow
statement and will consider amendments.
</TEXT>
