<HEADLINE>
FT  15 DEC 93 / Generators to learn their fate: Electricity regulator may
refer two leading power companies to MMC early next year
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Professor Stephen Littlechild, electricity industry regulator, is expected
to make a long-awaited statement today on the UK's two largest power
generators but is unlikely to reach a final decision on whether to refer
them to the Monopolies and Mergers Commission.
Although he has previously promised to make a decision on National Power and
PowerGen by the end of the year, it is likely that he will give them about a
month to respond to demands in his statement.
That would open up the possibility of a referral to the commission in the
early part of the year. Any delay will deepen the uncertainty over the
government's plans to sell its 40 per cent stakes in the companies in the
next financial year. The holdings are worth in excess of Pounds 3bn.
Prof Littlechild promised in the summer to make a decision on referring the
generators after sharp rises in prices in the electricity wholesale pool
through which power is traded in England and Wales.
He had already been examining their costs and profit margins.
The regulator's action followed widespread criticism from large energy
users. The users, who suffer the most from the price rises, buy their power
supplies directly from the pool rather than from an electricity supplier.
Prof Littlechild said that referring the generators would be one of several
options if he found that the prices they charge for running their generating
sets are unacceptably high.
He has also been considering whether to introduce price controls to limit
the charges that the generators levy or whether to reach an agreement with
them on the sale of some of their plant.
The generators have been arguing that either option would be unacceptable
because the prices they charge provide them with only a reasonable rate of
return.
Some analysts believe the generators would prefer to risk the consequences
of a commission reference rather than accept price controls or agree to
voluntary disposals.
Prof Littlechild's statement today is one of several expected within the
next few weeks.
He is also considering an appeal by large energy users over proposed reforms
to the bidding process in the electricity pool.
In addition, Nuclear Electric has asked him to give it a licence to allow it
to sell power directly to industrial customers.
Today's statement on the generators is expected to be given to the Stock
Exchange early this morning.
</TEXT>
<XX>
