<HEADLINE>
FT  15 DEC 93 / N&amp;P to sweep away obsolete accounts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SCHEHERAZADE DANESHKHU
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
National &amp; Provincial, the eighth-largest building society, is to transfer
Pounds 380m held by 600,000 savers in 40 obsolete accounts into new
accounts, most of which will pay higher interest than the old ones.
The society estimated that about Pounds 20bn was languishing in obsolete
bank and building society accounts in the UK, depriving investors of up to
Pounds 800m a year that they would earn in other accounts.
The N&amp;P savers - accounting for 25 per cent of customers but only 5 per cent
of savers' deposits - will be invited by letter to move to new accounts. If
they do not reply the society will move the accounts for them. Savers will
not have the option of staying with the old accounts - all will be closed.
It says that no saver will be worse off as a result of the automatic
transfer and that many will earn up to 4.5 percentage points gross above
their current rate. Savers will be able to retain special features of an old
account, such as standing orders, even if they are not a feature of the new
one.
Mr Stephen Geraghty, N&amp;P director of customer engagement, said savings on
administration costs would be small compared with the Pounds 5m it would pay
in extra interest. N&amp;P has seven investment accounts for new customers.
The society has spent Pounds 15m a year since 1991 on a campaign to keep
depositors informed about savings rates. About 1m customers have moved to
new accounts as a result. N&amp;P says it will be rid of obsolete accounts by
the end of March. If so, it will be the first building society to sweep its
savings cupboard clean of old accounts.
At least half of N&amp;P's obsolete accounts are the legacy of mergers and many
date back to the days of the Provincial and Burnley building societies which
merged in 1982 to form N&amp;P. Mr Andy Marchant, savings manager, said: 'Very
occasionally someone may not want to move because they are fond of an
account belonging to an old society that they are still loyal to.'
Obsolete accounts include the Whitehaven Old Series which pre-dates the
second world war. There are only 13 savers, earning 0.5 per cent a year
gross. 'It is quite possible that the customers may be deceased,' said Mr
Marchant.
The Burnley Old Series dates back to 1984, while the Keighley account has
only 12 savers.
</TEXT>
