<HEADLINE>
FT  15 DEC 93 / Consumers' Association embarrassed at being found out
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
The Consumers' Association yesterday admitted to being embarrassed after the
Advertising Standards Authority found it guilty of misleading advertising.
The authority upheld a complaint by a reader of New Scientist over a leaflet
promoting a prize draw run by the association's Which? magazine.
The leaflet was headed: 'We've doubled your chances of winning the Pounds
250,000 grand first prize. Specially for readers of New Scientist.' It went
on: 'We usually offer six prize draw numbers but for you we have allocated
12 numbers.'
The complainant maintained that if everyone received 12 numbers, the chance
of winning would remain the same. The association admitted that the insert
appeared in 90 magazines, though it said most entries would have come from
mailings offering six numbers.
</TEXT>
