<HEADLINE>
FT  15 DEC 93 / Consumer group misled readers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DIANE SUMMERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Consumers' Association yesterday admitted to being embarrassed after the
Advertising Standards Authority found it guilty of misleading advertising.
The authority upheld a complaint by a reader of New Scientist over a leaflet
promoting a prize draw run by the association's Which? magazine.
The leaflet, inserted in New Scientist, was headed: 'We've doubled your
chances of winning the Pounds 250,000 grand first prize. Specially for
readers of New Scientist.' It went on to state: 'We usually offer six prize
draw numbers but for you we have allocated 12 numbers.'
The complainant maintained that if everyone received 12 numbers, the chance
of winning would remain the same. The association admitted that the insert
appeared in 90 magazines, but said most respondents would have come from
mailings offering six numbers.
The authority said it was 'concerned that the insert implied that the 12
numbers were unique to readers of the New Scientist' and upheld the
complaint.
Ms Lesley Godwin, the Consumers' Association head of marketing, said
yesterday: 'The ASA is there to monitor advertising and it's absolutely
right that they should monitor ours just as much as anybody else's.
'It is embarrassing and I'm sorry it happened but if that is the way the ASA
have interpreted it (the British Code of Advertising Practice) I obviously
accept their judgment. We'll make sure that we don't take that slant in the
future.'
</TEXT>
