<HEADLINE>
FT  15 DEC 93 / Largest companies improve liquidity
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER NORMAN, Economics Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Britain's large industrial and commercial companies improved their
short-term liquidity position in the third quarter as they used the proceeds
of share and bond issues to build up current financial assets and repay
short-term borrowings.
Seasonally adjusted figures released by the Central Statistical Office
yesterday showed that the overall liquidity ratio of large UK companies
increased to an estimated 123 per cent at the end of the third quarter from
111 per cent at mid-year.
The ratio measures current assets maturing in less than a year as a share of
liabilities that have to be repaid in less than a year. It is based on a
survey of 350 of Britain's biggest companies and gives an indication of the
short-term financial strength of the large-company sector.
The liquidity ratio of large manufacturing companies increased to 105 per
cent at the end of September from 96 per cent at the end of June.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
