<HEADLINE>
FT  15 DEC 93 / Construction prices forecast to rise 8%
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW TAYLOR, Construction Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Construction prices are forecast to rise by 8 per cent during the next two
years, casting 'doubt on the chancellor's assertion that falling prices will
offset cuts in spending on roads and housing', says a survey published
today.
The survey, by the building-cost information service of the Royal
Institution of Chartered Surveyors, says builders faced with rising material
costs will be forced to increase prices.
Its forecasts are based on analysis of tenders accepted for building schemes
during the past three months.
The findings fly in the face of the Mr Kenneth Clarke's assertion in the
Budget that falling prices will enable the government to cut public spending
without damaging construction programmes.
Mr Christopher Vickers, a senior partner at quantity surveyors EC Harris and
construction spokesman for the institution, said construction prices had
fallen by a fifth since 1989. Building contractors could no longer afford to
absorb rising material prices, and as a result were increasing tender
prices.
Prices of constructional steel, cement, concrete, plasterboard, engineering
bricks and some types of glass have all risen this year and more increases
are likely, say material producers.
The institution says the knock-on effect will require contractors to raise
prices by 2.5 per cent between the fourth quarter of this year and the
fourth quarter of 1994. It says further increases in 1994-95 would push
prices up by 8 per cent over two years. The value of new commissions won by
architects fell by 5 per cent during the three months to the end of
September compared with the previous quarter, says a survey by the Royal
Institute of British Architects published today.
The survey, which is a good guide to future order trends in the construction
industry, says the fall was due partly to the ending of capital allowances
for industrial building.
None the less, the decline emphasised the 'fragility of the construction
industry recovery'. New commissions to architects had risen in each of the
two previous quarters.
More architects (27 per cent) expected workloads to increase than those (21
per cent) expecting work to reduce. But the positive balance had fallen to 6
percentage points from 14 percentage points.
</TEXT>
