<HEADLINE>
FT  15 DEC 93 / Anger over change to new agency rules
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT RICE and STEWART DALBY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
British companies which have sacked their commercial agents and renegotiated
their agency agreements to reduce the impact of new rules bringing UK law
into line with Europe may lose money following last-minute changes.
Companies had been advised, on the basis of draft regulations issued by the
Department of Trade and Industry in June, to consider renegotiating their
agreements because cancelling them after January 1 could cost between Pounds
5,000 and Pounds 80,000 per agreement in compensation.
The regulations, which will apply to any agency agreement in force on
January 1, are designed to give self-employed commercial agents greater
protection. They make it harder for companies to terminate agreements and
guarantee agents compensation if sacked.
The draft regulations provided that compensation should be paid for any
damage suffered by the agent following termination of the agreement.
But after complaints that this left companies open to pay unlimited damages
the government has made a last-minute change to the regulations to allow
industry to cap compensation.
Instead of paying damages companies can agree to indemnify the agent for a
sum equivalent to a maximum of one year's commission if the agreement is
terminated.
The change, which was set out in the final regulations published on Monday,
gives companies greater flexibility in negotiating new agreements.
Mr Ian Campbell, director-general of the Institute of Export, welcomed the
change but said: 'I can imagine a lot of companies will be annoyed if they
have acted on advice and changed their agreements, and will now have to
spend money to change them again.'
Mr Colin Dawson, managing director of Frank Whitelegg, which makes coil
winding machines and equipment for electric-motor repairs, said: 'It must be
a good idea to limit the compensation. Many companies could have been in for
an expensive time if the directive went through unchanged.'
Mr Tim Foster, of City solicitors Warner Cranston, said companies which
renegotiated agreements in anticipation of the new law were annoyed that
they had to change them again before January 1.
The DTI said yesterday it had been made clear that the regulations published
in June were only a draft and that changes could be made to the final text.
It added: 'We would never advise people to give advice to industry on the
basis of a draft.'
But Ms Rebecca Attree, an agency law specialist with London solicitors
Laytons, pointed out that even those clients who had held back from
renegotiating their agreements in case there were last-minute changes to the
rules were irritated. 'They now find they have very little time left to meet
the deadline - 10 days to be exact,' she said.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
