<HEADLINE>
FT  15 DEC 93 / Lawyers told to end court 'abuse'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN MASON, Law Courts Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Lawyers in serious fraud cases were warned yesterday by an Old Bailey judge
not to go on 'fishing expeditions' which were forbidden by law and an abuse
of court processes.
Judge Neil Denison made his remarks as he discharged three witness summonses
obtained by lawyers acting for Mr Mohammed Baqi against accountants Price
Waterhouse, the Bank of England and Treasury solicitors.
Mr Baqi, former managing director of Attock Oil, is due to face trial next
year on charges arising from the collapse of the Bank of Credit and Commerce
International. He is charged with dishonestly supplying documents to BCCI's
auditors Price Waterhouse.
The judge said the summons against Price Waterhouse required the firm to
produce all the documents in the BCCI case.
This was no more than 'a fishing expedition' in the hope that a trawl
through the vast amount of papers which Price Waterhouse would have to
analyse at their own expense might produce something useful to the defence,
he said.
The summonses against the Bank of England and Treasury solicitors had a
similar purpose.
The judge said: 'This sort of fishing expedition is expressly forbidden by
law and to try to get it by witness summons is an abuse of the process of
the court.'
When judges and lawyers engaged in large fraud trials were constantly
exhorted by the Court of Appeal to narrow the issues to be considered by
juries the issue of witness summonses such as these would do nothing to
simplify the trial, he said.
</TEXT>
