<HEADLINE>
FT  15 DEC 93 / Warning that EU fisheries deal could be imposed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN BROWN, Political Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The government appeared last night to be preparing for a European Union
fisheries deal with Spain and Portugal which opposition MPs claim will
outrage the UK fishing industry.
Mr Michael Jack, fisheries minister, warned the Commons that a deal might be
imposed by the EU fisheries council in Brussels on Monday, in spite of
British and Irish objections.
The government also announced that legislation restricting the number of
days on which fishing vessels can put to sea has been suspended following a
court challenge by fishermen. The High Court has referred the so-called
'days at sea legislation' to the European Court.
The government refused to confirm that a Pounds 25m decommissioning scheme
designed to help trawler owners leave the industry will continue after next
year. Mr Jack said ministers wanted to reconsider all the options for
meeting fishing quotas set by the fisheries council.
The issue is complicated by the requirement for a decision by the end of
this year on a EU fisheries regime to replace the transitional arrangements
for Spain and Portugal. The existing regime, which expires in 1996, has
assisted UK fishermen by limiting access to territorial waters for Spanish
and Portuguese vessels.
British ministers have argued that overall controls on catches must be
increased to compensate for the impending relaxation of the restrictive
regime. Only Ireland has given strong support to this position, raising
fears that Britain will be outvoted.
Opposition MPs urged the government to abandon the days-at-sea legislation,
and guarantee the future of the decommissioning scheme to help reduce the
British fleet. Mr Gavin Strang, shadow agriculture minister, said: 'This
decision was another botched opportunity. What the industry needed was a
clear-cut decision that days-at-sea restrictions had gone for good.'
He added that the government's refusal to guarantee the future of the
decommissioning scheme was 'petulant.' The suspension of the days-at-sea
rule strengthened the case for an enhanced decommissioning scheme.
Argentine anger, Page 28
</TEXT>
