<HEADLINE>
FT  15 DEC 93 / Beckett slams move to cut sick-pay cash
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ and KEVIN BROWN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Planned reductions in the statutory sick-pay subsidy would impose
'substantial' costs on small employers, in spite of assurances from
ministers that the changes should reduce industry's costs, the Labour party
said yesterday.
Mrs Margaret Beckett, Labour's deputy leader, told the Commons that the
government had deceived its backbenchers by disguising the true impact of
changes in the sickness benefit rules and rushing them through parliament
this week. She said that reductions in sick-pay subsidy for employers and
increases in National Insurance Contributions (NIC) for employees were
taxation items deserving a considered debate by MPs.
Ministers pressed ahead with plans to get both bills through their Commons
stages by tomorrow, however, saying that they had already been well
discussed in both the Queen's Speech and Budget debates in recent weeks.
Mr Tony Newton, leader of the Commons, said when introducing a guillotine
motion to curtail debate on the legislation that neither bill was 'long and
complicated'. Both had to be on the statute book by February if employers
were to be presented with a timely indication of their new costs.
Mrs Beckett said small employers paying less than Pounds 20,000 a year in
national insurance would face bigger costs because they would be getting no
subsidy for employees who were sick for up to four weeks. She said surveys
suggested that the average employee was rarely sick for longer.
Ministers said the increased costs were offset by recent cuts in the NIC
rate for employers.
Mr John Smith, the Labour leader, told Labour MPs in a letter released last
night that it was 'indefensible' that the sick-pay and social-security
contributions bills should be forced to pass all their parliamentary stages
in one day.
He said the opposition was determined to continue its campaign of not
co-operating with the government when parliament resumed.
His statement appeared designed to dispel rumours circulating at Westminster
that the campaign, triggered by the guillotine proposals, would be quietly
dropped when the Commons went into recess for three weeks on Friday.
</TEXT>
