<HEADLINE>
FT  15 DEC 93 / Labour attacks rises in cost of NHS bureaucracy
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr John Smith, the leader of the opposition, accused a leading NHS executive
of 'grotesque mismanagement of public funds' as Labour yesterday stepped up
its campaign against bureaucracy in the National Health Service.
At prime minister's question time in the House of Commons, Mr Smith claimed
recent reforms of the NHS had allowed health organisations to spend more
money on bureaucracy and public relations.
'It is disgraceful that in the health service the sums of money being spent
on increased bureaucracy, on huge salaries and perks for managers and on
glossy public relations seem totally out of control,' he said.
He referred to Sir Robin Buchanan, chairman of the NHS Supplies Authority
and a former Tory councillor, whose organisation was recently criticised for
spending decisions.
Mr Smith said that the organisation had 'wasted hundreds of thousands of
pounds changing a single word in their name'.
In reply Mr John Major said that spending on NHS administration was 'very
tightly examined and controlled' and that more patients were being treated
than ever before.
The prime minister added that NHS administration amounted to only 2 per cent
of total costs. 'There are very few companies that could match that,' he
said.
However, Mr Smith's attack comes amid signs of disquiet within the cabinet
over the cost of NHS reforms. Health service officials have said that Mrs
Virginia Bottomley, the health secretary, is privately concerned about
recent increases in NHS managers' salaries. Mr John Redwood, the Welsh
Secretary, also issued a strong attack last month on growing NHS
bureaucracy.
Under the NHS reforms regional health authorities have been given greater
autonomy for spending on hospital and ambulance services. Ministers say that
greater competition in the health service should encourage institutions to
keep costs low.
But Mr Alan Milburn, a Labour Treasury spokesman, said yesterday: 'There is
a very powerful message to get across about the extent of costs under the
current administration and the increase in bureaucracy.'
