<HEADLINE>
FT  15 DEC 93 / Homosexual protection reinstated
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   DENVER
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A judge in the US state of Colorado struck down yesterday a measure that
would have banned all state laws to protect homosexuals, Reuter reports from
Denver.
The measure, which arose from a citizens' initiative and became an amendment
to the state constitution in November 1992, set off a national boycott and
has cost the state millions of dollars in revenue from conventions. Various
groups declined to hold gatherings in Colorado while the amendment was in
place.
Denver District Court Judge Jeffrey Bayless ruled the measure
unconstitutional yesterday. He had earlier blocked implementation of the
amendment until his final decision.
The measure would have repealed existing ordinances designed to protect
homosexuals from discrimination while prohibiting the enactment of similar
laws in the state.
</TEXT>
