<HEADLINE>
FT  15 DEC 93 / Business community happy to see Sinn Fein at negotiating
table
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TIM COONE and JIMMY BURNS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Ninety-five per cent of Ulster's business community would be content to see
Sinn Fein at the negotiating table as part of the search for peace if the
IRA were to abandon violence for a substantial period, according to a
Financial Times poll, write Tim Coone and Jimmy Burns.
Only a handful of companies share the view of the Rev Ian Paisley of the
Democratic Unionist party, who argues Sinn Fein should indefinitely be
excluded from the political process.
Ulster executives also back the politically controversial proposal which has
been at the heart of Dublin's peace plan to test any political settlement
through separate referendums in both parts of Ireland.
The survey - the first of its kind - will hearten the London and Dublin
governments as it shows that senior executives firmly back their efforts to
achieve peace. But the executives do not believe that either the IRA or
Loyalist paramilitaries can be defeated militarily.
Financial Times reporters sought the views of 80 chief executives of
Northern Ireland's leading businesses last week. Fifty-six responded and
they were divided about the prospects of a settlement, with optimists
roughly matching pessimists.
More than 60 per cent were prepared for the British government to concede
enhanced north-south structures for economic co-operation to achieve a
settlement.
