<HEADLINE>
FT  15 DEC 93 / Russian reformists pin their hopes on Yeltsin's support
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LEYLA BOULTON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MOSCOW
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The survival of economic reforms in Russia depends on President Boris
Yeltsin's will to push them forward, leaders of Russia's divided and shaken
pro-reform camp said yesterday.
The most popular reform party Russia's Choice become more confident that, in
coalition with the three other main reformist parties, it could command more
seats than the combined anti-reform forces of Mr Vladimir Zhirinovsky's
neo-fascist Liberal Democratic party, Communists, and Agrarians.
The earliest results were for parliamentary seats being selected by
proportional representation from party lists. First results yesterday for
seats filled on a first-past-the-post basis suggest that reformists may have
benefited by being unaffiliated. Reformists seem to be winning such seats
because many are former officials whose names were recognised by voters.
The latest results for the seats being drawn from party lists which are
being determined by proportional representation, gave Mr Zhirinovsky 24 per
cent, followed by Russia's Choice with 15 per cent, the Communists with 11
per cent, and others, including Mr Yavlinsky's Yabloko bloc, about around 7
per cent.
Although serious bargaining on forming a new government was delayed as
participants waited for proper 'working results' before committing
themselves, the main parties spelt out their conditions for joining the
government.
Mr Zhirinovsky, whose ultimate goal is the presidency, said he would join a
coalition government only if his party could occupy the foreign ministry,
defence, security and interior ministries.
Yesterday he adopted a more moderate tone compared with his on-the-stump
comments, in an effort to soothe critics fearful of his ultra-right and
expansionist platform.
He promised not to'destabilise' the situation if he was left out of the
government, indicating that he would use parliament to increase his
popularity.
However, all the main pro-reform parties have excluded any co-operation with
Mr Zhirinovsky.
Mr Yeltsin, who has said he would use his new powers to pursue democracy and
reforms, has made no comment about Mr Zhirinovsky's electoral success.
Mr Grigory Yavlinsky, leader of the second largest reformist party after
Russia's Choice, said the reformers' success would depend entirely on how
President Yeltsin used the sweeping and permanent powers granted to him by
Russia's newly approved constitution.
Mr Yavlinsky said any new cabinet would have to be homogeneous and not like
the present government in which 'one third is building communism, one third
is building capitalism, and a third are looking after their personal
affairs.' He said it was also essential to give up attempts to dash to
financial stabilisation overnight because the fight against inflation would
only lead to 'bloody clashes'.
He said the electoral victory of Mr Zhirinovsky's 'national-socialist' party
of was in large part a reaction against reforms which had been harsh and
incoherent.
