<HEADLINE>
FT  14 DEC 93 / International Company News: Hungary mounts rescue of 10
commercial banks
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NICHOLAS DENTON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BUDAPEST
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The Hungarian government yesterday unveiled a two-stage Dollars 1.4bn
bailout for 10 commercial banks whose capital has been wiped out by loan
losses.
In the first stage later this month the state will inject Ft110bn (Dollars
1.1bn) to restore solvency to Magyar Hitel Bank, Kereskedelmi Bank and
Budapest Bank, the country's three largest commercial banks, and five
smaller financial institutions.
On average the banks have negative capital equivalent to about 15 per cent
of risk-weighted assets and the infusion is needed just to raise the banks'
capital adequacy to zero.
The rescue is necessary before the closing of the 1993 accounts to rebuild
confidence in the troubled banks after a World Bank aide-memoire declared
them 'technically insolvent'.
A further recapitalisation in the first half of 1994 will include two more
banks and raise capital adequacy ratios to at least 4 per cent at a cost of
an estimated Ft30bn.
The government hopes that its support will speed privatisation of the banks
and that the contribution of new investors will provide the final boost to
take capital adequacy ratios to the 8 per cent standard set by the
Basle-based Bank for International Settlements.
Hitel Bank has the largest call on the government's funds with a capital
need of over Ft50bn. It is the largest commercial bank and main lender to
the engineering companies which have suffered most from the collapse of
Comecon markets.
The latest commitment comes on top of the state's assumption of bad debts
from the banking sector at a cost of Ft100bn in 1992 and a similar Ft40bn
exchange earlier this year.
The government is spreading the burden by effecting the recapitalisation
through 20-year bonds. Yesterday's announcement nevertheless takes to nearly
Ft300bn the total cost of Hungary's efforts to shore up its banking system.
In return, the finance ministry is exacting a heavy price in terms of lost
independence for banks participating in the government's 'consolidation'
scheme.
The capital increase will dilute the shareholdings of existing investors and
the ministry has said it intends to demand a controlling golden share in any
bank in which its stake does not reach 75 per cent.
</TEXT>
