<HEADLINE>
FT  14 DEC 93 / PO chief warns of increase in charges
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROLAND RUDD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Post Office investment plans and profitability are being put at risk because
of uncertainty over the government's review, the corporation said yesterday.
In an outspoken attack on ministers for failing to make up their minds, Mr
Mike Heron, chairman, threatened an increase in postal charges if the
government did not change the present regime.
He said: 'The long uncertainty is highly damaging, especially when coupled
to the trebling this year of the cash we have to pay the Treasury. I do not
believe the status quo can continue.'
The Post Office's external finance limit target - the amount it has to pay
the government - has risen to Pounds 230m next year, and is set at Pounds
210m for the following year.
In the short term, Mr Bill Cockburn, chief executive, said it could meet the
targets only at the expense of capital expenditure and investment. In the
long term, it would mean higher stamp prices and might even threaten the
corporation's 15-year history of profitability.
The Department of Trade and Industry, which initiated the review 18 months
ago, is understood to have ruled out full-scale privatisation, but is known
to be sympathetic to its call for greater commercial freedom.
It said yesterday its review, which is not expected to be published until
early next year, was 'complex and difficult'. It added that pressure on
public finances meant that everyone, including the Post Office, had to make
a contribution to the PSBR.
However, Mr Edward Leigh, who was responsible for the Post Office until
dismissed as trade and industry minister last summer, accused the government
of a 'political funk' for not privatising the corporation.
Mr Robin Cook, Labour's shadow trade and industry secretary, said: 'The
strong language which Mike Heron uses to complain about the government is
unprecedented for a chairman of a public corporation.'
Editorial Comment, Page 17
</TEXT>
