<HEADLINE>
FT  14 DEC 93 / Behaviour blamed on poor teaching
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Ofsted, the education watchdog, said yesterday that bad behaviour in schools
was caused by poor teaching.
It said that most classrooms in England and Wales were calm and orderly, but
it noted concern that exclusions of pupils from schools were increasing
sharply, and that there were 'unacceptably wide' variations between schools
in the nature of offences which would lead to exclusion.
Ofsted said: 'For most pupils, good behaviour is associated with a
well-planned and varied curriculum and lively, stimulating teaching.
Expectations of high standards achieved through demanding tasks leave little
time for, or interest in, misbehaviour.'
