<HEADLINE>
FT  14 DEC 93 / Output prices held steady
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER MARSH, Economics Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Manufacturers have barely increased their prices since the summer according
to government figures released yesterday that illustrate the weakness of
inflationary pressures.
Prices of materials and energy bought by manufacturers were 1.8 per cent
lower in November than 12 months earlier, the biggest yearly drop since July
last year.
The figures from the Central Statistical Office underline how inflation has
been falling under the influence of low demand, small increases in wage
costs and a fall in the prices of many commodities such as oil.
Sterling's 10.4 per cent depreciation since Britain's exit from the exchange
rate mechanism in September last year has failed to spur inflation in spite
of higher import costs.
Between July and last month prices of manufactured goods for domestic sale
at the wholesale level have risen by just 0.2 per cent on a basis that does
not include adjustments for seasonal factors.
Prices were unchanged last month from October. In the year to November,
prices rose by 3.6 per cent - the smallest yearly increase since February
and a figure slightly lower than City expectations. In the year to October
output prices rose 4 per cent.
Excluding food, drink, tobacco and petrol - whose prices are affected by tax
changes - wholesale prices of factory goods rose 3.2 per cent in the year to
November, the same as in the year to October.
Adjusted for seasonal changes, prices of these classes of products rose 0.2
per cent in November compared with October while they increased 1.1 per cent
between July and last month on the same basis.
The fall in the year to November of prices of materials and fuel bought by
manufacturers came in spite of a rise last month in the costs of electricity
to large industrial groups. In the year to October, overall prices of
materials and fuel rose 0.5 per cent.
Prices of crude oil bought by manufacturers fell by 16.2 per cent in the
year to last month. Over the same period prices of UK-produced foodstuffs
fell 3.3 per cent, while prices of general fuels, chemicals, metals and
imported foods increased by 0.6 per cent, 0.9 per cent, 0.2 per cent and 4.9
per cent respectively.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
