<HEADLINE>
FT  14 DEC 93 / Budget 'likely to halve growth in construction'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW TAYLOR, Construction Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
One of the construction industry's foremost leading forecasting bodies has
halved its projections for growth next year, blaming measures announced in
the Budget last month.
The National Council of Building Material Producers, which represents more
than 2,000 companies, yesterday forecast that construction output would rise
by only 0.5 per cent next year after falling this year. Before the Budget
the council had been forecasting a 1 per cent rise.
Mr Peter Roberts, chairman of the forecasting panel, said growth would slow
as a result of reductions in government spending on housing associations and
roads. He said: 'The chancellor's Budget was not one for the construction
industry in the short term.'
He was also concerned that government attempts to encourage greater
private-sector investment in toll roads, railways and other infrastruc-ture
would not come through quickly enough to offset public spending cuts
elsewhere.
He said: 'It is essential the private finance initiative is kept at the top
of the political agenda and more projects are seen to come to fruition.'
The council has not altered its forecast that output will fall by 2 per cent
this year. This would mean that the value of output in constant 1985 prices
has fallen by almost 17 per cent since 1990. The council expects the pace of
recovery will accelerate in 1995 when it expects output to rise by 2 per
cent.
It says that the slower rate of growth forecast for next year was because of
a Pounds 900m cut in the Housing Corporation development programme. It
expects this will reduce the number of homes started by the public sector
next year from 42,000 to 36,000, falling to 33,000 in 1995.
Central government spending on roads was expected to fall by 7 per cent
while tough spending constraints on councils would affect investment in
local roads and council house repair and maintenance, the council said.
But it did not expect phased reductions in mortgage tax relief, also
announced in the Budget, to inhibit the recovery in the housing market. It
expects the number of private-sector starts to rise from 140,000 to 150,000
next year, increasing to 160,000 in 1995.
Factory and warehouse building was forecast to rise by 5 per cent next year.
The rate of decline in commercial construction, mainly offices and shops,
was expected to fall from 20 per cent to 5 per cent next year. Commercial
output, however, was forecast to rise by 5 per cent in 1995.
</TEXT>
