<HEADLINE>
FT  14 DEC 93 / New town body to offer land as prize
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL CHEESERIGHT, Midlands Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Commission for the New Towns, responsible for development and sales of
publicly owned assets in 21 English towns, is offering prizes of land at a
discount, or even free, to winners of a competition between councils and
private-sector partners, Paul Cheeseright, Midlands Correspondent, writes.
It is asking councils which have new towns in their areas to combine with
companies to submit plans by March for housing, commercial or leisure
developments on or near commission land. Winning plans would receive land at
less than its commercial value. The competition, announced yesterday in
Telford to coincide with the new town's 25th anniversary, is designed not
only to hasten development in the new towns but also to accelerate
commission land sales.
The commission is being wound up by the government in 1998, by which time it
hopes to have sold the assets in the new towns.
Since 1979 it has raised Pounds 2bn for the Treasury. Its contribution in
1992-93 was Pounds 165m and, with property markets still uncertain, is
expected to be about the same this year.
Assets for disposal include 9.6m sq ft of commercial premises and 18,000
acres of land. The largest concentrations of land are in Milton Keynes and
Telford, each of which has about 4,000 acres controlled by the commission.
No estimates have been drawn up of the effect of cheap land disposals on the
commission's annual contribution to the Treasury. This contribution is used
to offset part of the Department of Environment's urban and regional
spending. But the commission noted that the use of land which it could not
immediately expect to sell would enhance property values in the town where
the development took place.
The competition is being run jointly by the commission and the Association
of District Councils. It follows the established government policy of using
a contest to encourage the formation of partnerships between the public and
private sectors for a specific purpose or development.
The commission was anxious that its competition should not be seen as a
device for selling off land at distress rates. Rather, it said, the
reduction in the price of any land would be related to the quality of the
scheme being advanced by a council and its partners.
The English new towns, in addition to Milton Keynes and Telford, are
Aycliffe, Basildon, Bracknell, Central Lancashire, Corby, Crawley, Harlow,
Hatfield, Hemel Hempstead, Northampton, Peterborough, Peterlee, Redditch,
Runcorn, Skelmersdale, Stevenage, Warrington, Washington and Welwyn Garden
City.
</TEXT>
