<HEADLINE>
FT  14 DEC 93 / George plans shake-up as role changes
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER NORMAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Bank of England is planning an internal restructuring that could result
in its operations being grouped in two broad 'wings'. One wing would focus
on achieving monetary stability and the other on ensuring the stability of
the financial system.
Mr Eddie George, the Bank's governor, and its senior directors worked out
the plan to replace the Bank's present tangled allocation of
responsibilities in more than a dozen divisions and three departments at a
special weekend meeting earlier this month.
The plan, which is viewed in Threadneedle Street as a separate issue from
the debate over whether to give the Bank greater independence from the
Treasury in its conduct of monetary policy, is still being thrashed out.
If carried through, it will be the Bank's first significant internal
restructuring since 1980. The plan follows last July's change of top
management when Mr George moved from being deputy governor to governor and
Mr Rupert Pennant-Rea, former editor of the Economist, was appointed deputy.
Mr Pennant-Rea has formed a working party to handle the restructuring.
The plan to create a monetary wing responsible for price stability
recognises the more explicit counter-inflationary role that has been given
to the Bank since Britain left the exchange rate mechanism of the European
Monetary System in September last year.
The wing would include the parts of the Bank responsible for monetary
operations, including the markets section, as well as some banking
activities and the economic analysis division.
Banking supervision would be the main responsibility of the financial
stability wing, which would also take over the Bank's duties for making the
City function well.
These include the non-statutory supervision of bullion and foreign exchange
markets and gilt-edged marketmakers (Gemms) as well as its work on
payments-and-settlements systems, stock exchange dealings systems and
Lloyd's, the insurance market.
Officials stressed yesterday that the plans were still a 'strategic vision'
that would be refined over the next six months. There is no intention to
reorganise the Bank in one 'big bang' and no timetable for the full
implementation of the ideas.
The personnel consequences have still to be worked out. It is unclear how
the Bank's executive directors fit in the new structure, although the
imminent departure of Mr Andrew Crockett, the international director, to
head the Bank for International Settlements in Basle and the approaching
retirement of Mr Tony Coleby, the director handling monetary issues, should
create some flexibility.
The proposed restructuring would not affect the Bank's 'court', which
advises the management on policy. Any big change in the court's structure
would require an act of parliament, which is unlikely unless the Bank is
given independence.
The planned management changes would be compatible with a more independent
Bank, however. The movement to give the Bank greater freedom is expected to
be boosted on Thursday when the Commons Treasury and civil service committee
publishes a report that is widely expected to support more autonomy for the
Bank.
New capital issues by UK borrowers last month totalled Pounds 4.635bn of
which Pounds 3.592bn was denominated in sterling, the Bank said yesterday.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
