<HEADLINE>
FT  14 DEC 93 / Deputy Bank chief warns of rate rises
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER NORMAN, Economics Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Bank of England yesterday gave its clearest warning yet that Britain
would raise interest rates if sharp price increases by companies threatened
to push inflation through the top of its target range.
Mr Rupert Pennant-Rea, the Bank's deputy governor, entered the debate about
whether companies have raised margins excessively.
He stressed that conditions of low inflation required different corporate
policies, with companies aiming for higher sales rather than higher prices.
A month ago, Mr Eddie George, the Bank's governor, sparked controversy when
he said more than half of recent increases in manufacturers' output prices
came from higher margins.
The row was fuelled by Mr Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor, who said a sharp
10 per cent increase in export prices in the past year was a 'vivid
reminder' that UK management prefers higher returns rather than higher
volumes when competing overseas.
Yesterday, Mr Pennant-Rea denied that the Bank was telling managers how to
run their businesses.
However, he stressed that the government's aim of keeping the 12-month
change in the retail prices index, excluding mortgage interest payments,
within a range of 1 per cent to 4 per cent - and holding it in the lower
half of that range by the end of this parliament - would have a powerful
effect on companies' pricing policies.
'We plan to take inflation off the menu,' Mr Pennant-Rea told the City
branch of the Institute of Directors. That meant no big monetary boost to
pull the economy out of recession, no boom-bust cycle, and avoidance of
conditions that produced a big surge in wages.
Companies would not be able to raise prices on the assumption that
competitors were doing the same, he added.
Mr Pennant-Rea said that if companies raised prices beyond the target range,
'we, the policymakers, will raise interest rates. If firms show restraint,
aiming for bigger volumes rather than wider margins, then interest rates can
be restrained too.'
The deputy governor's warnings came against a background of disappointing
industrial production figures and official statistics showing only modest
inflationary pressures from producer prices.
Mr Pennant-Rea said the present low inflation climate opened the way for
companies to boost profits through higher volumes rather than prices. The
profitability of UK companies was 'pretty robust' and close to that in many
other countries. It meant companies would be pricing themselves out of the
market if they tried to boost their margins by raising prices.
With an inflation target, corporate price decisions had 'huge implications'
for the macroeconomic conditions that companies faced, he said.
'We are resolved to achieve overall price stability. Business will benefit
hugely from that,' he said.
But it would benefit even more if, in advance of that stability 'it begins
to think of the long term: of extra volumes and more market share as the
road to enduring profitability'.
Lex, Page 18
</TEXT>
