<HEADLINE>
FT  14 DEC 93 / Major claims EU follows his lead
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS, Political Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr John Major claimed yesterday that other European Union governments had
adopted Britain's agenda for economic recovery and were endorsing policies
which many had regarded as 'unthinkable' a few years ago.
In an uncompromising statement in the Commons, the prime minister told MPs
that the government had endorsed Mr Jacques Delors' plans for higher growth
and employment only because 'we took out the bits we rubbished.'
What remained, he added, was the British prescription of firm control of
public spending and inflation, open markets, decentralisation and de -
regulation and flexibility in Labour markets.
But Mr Major's account of the weekend summit of EU leaders drew scorn from
opposition leaders. Mr John Smith, the Labour leader, accused Mr Major of
backing in Brussels policies to boost employment but of failing to deliver
high-quality training and education in Britain.
The Labour leader also attacked Mr Major's refusal - underlined again in the
Commons exchanges - to agree to higher Community borrowing to finance major
European transport projects.
Mr Smith asked MPs: 'If projects make sense, what is so wrong about
borrowing for genuine investment in vital infrastructure projects that will
improve our economy, create jobs, stimulate growth and competitiveness and,
in the medium term, put our public finances in proper order?'
Mr Major said the EU had at last rejected 'outdated policies' involving
extra burdens on business and borrowing.
Stressing repeatedly the importance of a successful conclusion of the
present GATT round of world trade negotiations, Mr Major said that Europe
now agreed 'the only road to economic recovery is the one on which this
government is already embarked'.
</TEXT>
