<HEADLINE>
FT  14 DEC 93 / Last of Britain's pit ponies to be put out to pasture
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRIS TIGHE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Britain's last deep-mine pit ponies are to be put out to pasture by the end
of March when the final eight are to be made redundant at Ellington colliery
in Northumberland, Chris Tighe writes.
Ponies have been working in British mines for two centuries, and their use
grew rapidly from 1860 when women and children were forbidden from working
underground. In 1913, there were 68,000 ponies in mines from Kent to
Scotland. In spite of the increasing mechanisation of coal mining, ponies
have continued to play an important role at many collieries. At Sacriston
pit in County Durham they were used until eight years ago, being led out for
the last time (above) in 1985.
At Ellington the pit ponies work up to seven miles out under the North Sea
pulling tubs of salvaged steel girders. At present they live about 300 feet
underground in their stables, with a round-the-clock team of horsekeepers
and a number of fat, mouse-eating cats for company. Each pony is assigned to
a three-man team of miners and works the 8.30am to 3.15pm shift. They have
one week's holiday a year above ground. Contrary to mythology, they are not
blind.
By spring, British Coal hopes to have found all eight, mares and geldings
aged from nine to 20, suitable homes. However, the ponies cannot be ridden
because they have never been broken in.
'There's a great feeling of comradeship between man and pony,' said Mr Ian
Lavery, NUM miners' union lodge secretary at Ellington, where 650 men, more
than half the human workforce, are to lose their jobs by 1996.
There would be mixed feelings and sadness at the ponies going, he said, but
they had been well cared for. He added: 'British Coal probably look after
the ponies better than their own men.'
</TEXT>
