<HEADLINE>
FT  14 DEC 93 / Tories threaten to rebel over guillotine
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The government could face a rebellion by Tory backbenchers in the Commons
today when it takes its first steps to rush through two key pieces of
revenue-raising legislation.
Three backbench Tory MPs said last night that they were deeply unhappy about
today's 'guillotine' motion, which aims to get bills reducing the statutory
sick pay subsidy to employers and raising National Insurance contributions
from employees' through all their Commons stages by Thursday night. Mr
Richard Shepherd, MP for Arlidge-Brownhills, said that he would abstain from
voting on today's guillotine motion and on both bills later in the week. He
believes the decision to push the legislation through quickly is an
'infringement of free speech'.
The other two backbenchers, Mr Nicholas Winterton, MP for Macclesfield, and
Mr Patrick Cormack, MP for Staffordshire South, said that they were
considering abstaining, also in the belief that the guillotine will give MPs
too little time to consider the issues.
The government's majority of 17 means that ministers remain confident that
the legislation will pass on time and without hitches. But the rebellion
will put additional pressure on Tory whips after Labour's decision to
protest against the guillotine and abandon its arrangement to 'pair off' MPs
with opponents so that both can be absent during divisions.
Mr Derek Foster, Labour's chief whip, believes this move may make life
difficult for government whips, who will have to ensure that sufficient MPs
are in the Commons to vote the measures through.
Mr David Winnick, Labour MP for Walsall North, said there would be no
consensus over proposed reforms to the hours of Commons sittings 'as long as
the government treats the House with the contempt it is showing this week'.
If today's guillotine is passed, the Statutory Sick Pay Bill will be debated
for no more than six hours tomorrow, with MPs voting at 10pm. The debate
raising the National Insurance contribution will go through the same
curtailed procedures on Thursday. After consideration by the Lords, both
bills should be on the statute book in the new year.
It is not unusual for legislation to pass through the Commons at such speed,
but Labour says it is almost unprecedented so early in a parliamentary
session.
Ministers say the sick pay and National Insurance legislation have to be on
the statute book quickly so that employers can make provision for the
changes. The measures will raise about Pounds 2.5bn for the Exchequer next
year.
</TEXT>
