<HEADLINE>
FT  14 DEC 93 / Portillo indicates tough spending stance will stay
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER NORMAN, Economics Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The government's public expenditure control totals for 1995-96 and 1996-97
will almost certainly be adopted as the ceilings for next year's round of
public spending negotiations between the Treasury and other government
departments, Mr Michael Portillo, chief secretary to the Treasury, said
yesterday.
Signalling a continuation of the government's rigorous approach to public
spending, Mr Portillo told the Commons Treasury and civil service committee
that he expected the cabinet next summer would confirm the figures as the
remit for next autumn's spending round.
His reply indicated that non-cyclical expenditure, which has been set at
Pounds 251.3bn in 1994-95, will not be allowed to exceed Pounds 263bn in
1995-96 and Pounds 272.3bn in the following financial year. That would hold
the control totals to real increases of 0.9 per cent in 1995-96 and 1 per
cent in 1996-97.
Mr Portillo agreed with the committee that the tax increases planned in this
year's two Budgets would play an ever greater role in reducing the public
sector borrowing requirement over the coming three financial years. But he
said that some of the spending curbs announced in Mr Kenneth Clarke's Budget
last month would produce savings beyond the April 1997 limit to the
government's present spending plans.
Proposals to restructure invalidity and unemployment benefit would produce
savings after 1997, while more savings could emerge from the fundamental
reviews of spending priorities in large departments such as social security,
he said.
He disclosed that during the first half of next year the Treasury would be
investigating issues that transcend the boundaries between government
departments.
</TEXT>
