<HEADLINE>
FT  14 DEC 93 / Names' right to sue agents upheld
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
The Court of Appeal yesterday upheld the right of loss-making Names on the
Lloyd's insurance market to sue members' agents in a move that paves the way
for a series of legal actions next year.
The decision removes one of the final barriers to litigation by Names - the
individuals whose assets traditionally supported the insurance market - on
the Gooda Walker and Feltrim syndicates.
Sir Thomas Bingham, the Master of the Rolls, Lord Justice Hoffmann and Lord
Justice Henry ruled in the Court of Appeal that members' agents were
contractually responsible for any negligence by the management and
underwriters of syndicates they selected for Names. They did not grant leave
to appeal.
The ruling comes as the Names are deciding whether to accept a Pounds 900m
out-of-court settlement offered by Lloyd's.
The Gooda Walker Action Group is expected to write to its members at the end
of this week recommending that they reject Lloyd's settlement offer and
continue to pursue legal action.
</TEXT>
