<HEADLINE>
FT  14 DEC 93 / Brussels hits at generator over coal contracts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
National Power, the UK's largest generator, appears to be discriminating
against small, private-sector companies in five-year coal contracts
concluded last March, the European Commission's competition directorate
says.
Preliminary findings in an investigation by the directorate say National
Power is not justified in imposing a 10.5p per gigajoule difference between
prices it pays to state-owned British Coal and independent companies. A
confidential report by the directorate also finds that National Power
discriminates against opencast operators and in favour of deep mines in
allocating tonnages to private-sector operators.
National Power said yesterday it could not comment in detail on a report
which was not public. But it said it was confident that, when it had given a
full explanation, the commission would accept its position.
If the commission confirms its findings, the small operators are likely to
push for redress through the British courts.
The High Court is due to hear tomorrow and Thursday a separate dispute
involving National Power and South Wales and Monmouthsire Small Mines
Association over earlier contracts.
In the dispute involving National Power's existing five-year contracts with
independent producers, the commission's preliminary view says that the small
miners and blenders, who mix varying grades of coal, have been treated at
least as favourably as British Coal in the allocation of tonnages when they
are taken as a whole.
But it finds that National Power has disriminated in favour first of the
blenders and then the deep mines, both at the expense of the opencast
operators.
The report notes the commission has accepted the principle of a differential
between the price paid by generators to British Coal and independent
operators. This is because of additional costs associated with transport,
sulphur and investment when dealing with independent coal.
The commission's preliminary view is that the 10.5p gap is not entirely
justified but says it needs additional information to determine what the
differential should be.
It suggest the maximum should be 6.5p per gigajoule.
In a review of the commission's ruling, UK Coal, an FT newsletter, says
National Power may feel aggrieved in the ruling since it had done more to
protect the interest of private miners than other generators. However, the
differentials looked difficult to justify.
</TEXT>
