FT  14 DEC 93 / Vodafone granted fixed-wire licence
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW ADONIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Vodafone, the UK's largest mobile phone network operator, has been granted a
national licence to offer 'fixed-wire' services in competition with British
Telecommunications, Andrew Adonis writes.
Until now Vodafone, which has 1m mobile customers, has been forbidden from
building or operating a fixed network. It has been restricted to competing
with Cellnet, the mobile operator jointly owned by BT and Securicor, and
Mercury One-2-One, a joint venture between Mercury and US West.
Vodafone said it did not intend at present to compete head-on with BT. Mr
Terry Barwick, Vadafone's director of corporate affairs, said: 'The fixed
market is already highly competitive, and we intend to stick to what we do
best.'
The move follows a review two years ago which led the government to abolish
the BT/Mercury duopoly in the provision of fixed services.
