<HEADLINE>
FT  14 DEC 93 / World Trade News: GM and Poland reach deal on car assembly
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN DONE and CHRISTOPHER BOBINSKI
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LONDON, WARSAW
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
General Motors, the US carmaker, reached agreement with the Polish
authorities yesterday to begin car assembly in Warsaw, in a joint venture
with FSO, the Polish state-owned carmaker.
The deal, reached after more than two years of negotiations, marks an
important step forward in the modernisation of the eastern European car
industry.
In the first stage, the venture will assemble up to 10,000 four-door Opel
Astra small family cars a year from SKD (semi-knocked-down) kits supplied
from GM plants in western Europe.
GM will send already-painted car bodies from its assembly plant at Antwerp
for final trim and assembly in Warsaw. Major components such as engines and
transmissions will be supplied from its plant at Bochum, Germany.
Production will begin in the second half of next year.
At first, GM will invest DM9.4m (Pounds 3.73m) to take a 50 per cent stake
and management control in the venture, which will have a workforce of about
250. It will invest a further DM10m within a few months, which will increase
its stake to 65-70 per cent.
Under the terms of the deal, GM envisages moving later to a more ambitious
second stage in which cars would be assembled from CKD
(completely-knocked-down) kits, which would require body welding and
painting to be carried out in Poland.
Output for the second stage could be increased to up to 33,000 cars a year
on three shifts with a workforce of about 1,000. This stage would increase
total investment in the project to about Dollars 60m (Pounds 40.2m). At
present, GM has 32 Opel dealers in Poland and is aiming to increase this to
about 50 next year.
As part of the planned co-operation, GM will take part in developing the
automotive components supply industry in Poland.
Last week, it announced that ACG, the GM group's automotive components
subsidiary, with two of its worldwide divisions Packard Electric and Inland
Fisher Guide, had signed a memorandum of understanding with FSO and its
affiliate ZEM-ELK to set up a feasibility study of the establishment of
joint ventures in components areas such as wiring harnesses, lighting, and
metal and plastic components.
GM said that several other ACG components divisions were also in discussions
with potential Polish partners, within the FSO group and outside.
As a further part of the deal, GM will advise FSO on measures to modernise
production of the Polish carmaker's present out-dated Polonez car range,
originally launched in 1978, the design of which dates back to the 1960s.
For the longer term, GM will assist in evaluating a replacement for the
Polonez, and it is understood to be examining the possibility of producing a
new low-cost car in Poland smaller than its present Opel/Vauxhall Corsa
supermini.
Mr David Herman, chief executive of Opel, said yesterday that 'Poland could
certainly be a good place to produce an entry level car.'
Fiat, the Italian carmaker, which recently completed the takeover of FSM,
the other former state-owned carmaker, already uses Poland as its sole
assembly location for its Cinquecento small car for supply to all European
markets.
GM said yesterday that as part of its assembly deal the Polish authorities
had agreed not to impose an excise tax on its local production. A 15 per
cent excise duty is charged on imported cars.
Mr Marek Pol, the new Polish industry minister, said that GM would be exempt
from paying profit tax waivers up to the amount of its investment of DM9.4m.
'There have been no inducements other than those regularly extended to
foreign investors,' Mr Pol said yesterday. But the contract gives assurances
that the Polish government will compensate GM for any losses resulting from
future changes in tariff and tax conditions.
</TEXT>
